<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Yamato-e (大和絵), or "Japanese painting," is the classical native tradition that emerged in the Heian period in distinction to Chinese-influenced kara-e. Characterized by native subjects, narrative handscrolls (emakimono), screen and sliding-door compositions, and a refined palette keyed to the four seasons and courtly life, Yamato-e gave form to tales such as The Tale of Genji and scenes of famous places (meisho-e). It established a distinctly Japanese pictorial language that would influence later schools and remain central to the identity of Japanese art.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
